ment concerns, such as reducing poverty and improving health and fulfilling other basic needs. Nearly half of the course will be on managing such issues of human development issues (and indirectly, their intertwined nature with environmental problems). Where possible, we will show the links between environmental sustainability and poverty. While solutions to these problems may require the involvement of the private sector (firms), the public sector (government) and the community, firms are increasingly called on to reduce their negative impacts on the environment and humans alike. The course will focus in particular on how business can address sustainability issues. Sustainability issues often consist of complex interactions between human activity and the environment. The course will apply several academic perspectives to characterizing these problems and their possible solutions. The course first examines how particular patterns of economic and social development are manifested in past practices and developmental paths, such as unsustainable patterns of urbanization and industrialization. The private sector is an integral part of many problems and solutions, and as such, will be the main focus of the course. An important part of addressing sustainability is the use of various frameworks to help incorporate a sustainability perspective into firms’ strategies and operations. These often employ a systems perspective. To help characterize firm’ sustainability and determine appropriate courses of action, the course will cover also specific managerial tools and frameworks that help to characterize sustainability challenges and incorporate them into corporate plans include the Triple Bottom Line, Life-Cycle Assessment, and the Base of the Pyramid approach and its business models. Where necessary, material on and links to concepts of strategy, business models, stakeholder engagement, public policy (in terms of governance), and innovation will be made.While many of the sustainability concepts have a Western origin, because of our location in Asia, and the increasing importance of sustainability to the local and regional context, especial attention has been paid to relating each section of the course to Asia, even as the original material (concepts and experiences) is covered from the (non-Asian) country or region of origin. This will be done through a series of cases and examples, especially for the part of the course covering industrialization- and poverty-related sustainability issues. Examples of Asia-specific material introduced in past classes and continued this year include material on the early phases of Japan’s industrialization and pollution and its eventual social-regulatory reforms; China’s ongoing sustainability problems as it continues to industrialize; China’s renewable energy policy and planning; agro-based eco-industrial parks (industrial ecosystems) in Turkey; the ongoing poverty issues in the region, and solutions (technological and otherwise) as practiced in India and Bangladesh); and finally, issues that Singapore faces. Similarly, the poor in the East and in other developing regions face many of the same issues as seen in other developing and developed regions, and so cross-comparisons between different regions can yield many lessons.","info_instructors":["TED FEICHIN TSCHANG","Staff"]}},"MGMT304":{"name":"Entrepreneurial Leadership in Ethnic Chinese Business","data":{"info_career":"Undergraduate","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_academic_organization":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_description":"Since the mid-1980s intra-regional trade and investment links in East and Southeast Asia have expanded rapidly with the shift of production by firms from Japan and newly industrializing countries to lower-cost, neighboring countries. Ethnic Chinese from Hong Kong, Taiwan, Singapore, Malaysia or Indonesia are actively involved in these massive transformation and integration processes. The course will scrutinize their role as well as some of the (culturally biased) misperceptions about their business conduct. The degree, to which their extensive business networks succeed because of ethnic characteristics, or simply because of the sound application of good business practice, is a key issue that will be discussed throughout the course. Based on various corporate case studies and a multi-disciplinary explanatory framework, we will assess the role, characteristics and challenges of Chinese entrepreneurship and business networks in the People’s Republic of China, Vietnam, Malaysia, Singapore and Indonesia in an era of global market expansion.","info_instructors":["THOMAS MENKHOFF"]}},"MAND201":{"name":"Mandarin","data":{"info_career":"Undergraduate","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Social Sciences","info_academic_organization":"School of Social Sciences","info_description":"This course is design to equip you with elementary knowledge of the structure of Han Yu Pin Yin and the correct usage of vocabulary and grammar in daily conversation. Empowered with this knowledge and with the help of Chinese dictionary, you will be able to read all Chinese characters and pronounce them accurately. These skills provide a foundation in the usage of computer to enter Chinese characters.","info_instructors":["WANG SHENGYU","Staff"]}},"MGMT310":{"name":"Leading New Ventures to Growth","data":{"info_career":"Undergraduate","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_academic_organization":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_description":"In pursuing a business idea, an important issue for the entreprene