ription":"Antitrust, competition or anti-monopoly laws aim to prevent or discourage businesses from engaging in anticompetitive behaviour. From the enactment of the Sherman Act (1890) in the United States until the 1970s, competition laws existed only in a handful of industrialized countries. In the last few decades, however, many countries around the world have adopted competition policies and established independent competition authorities. The number of countries with competition laws has grown from around twenty in 1980 to more than a hundred by 2005. The Competition Commission of Singapore was established in 2005 while China’s first comprehensive competition law commenced in 2008. This course aims at giving students an introduction to the basic issues of competition law: market power and market definition, abuse of dominance, cartels and tacit collusion, vertical restraints, mergers and remedies.","info_instructors":["POH LIP HANG"]}},"ECON647":{"name":"Time Series Analysis and Forecasting","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - Economics (CW)","info_units":0.5,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Economics","info_academic_organization":"School of Economics GPO","info_description":"We cover selected topics in applied econometrics, specifically instrumental variable estimation and simultaneous equation models, vector autoregression models, error-correction models, panel data, and forecasting.  The emphasis is on application of these models rather than theoretical results, with hands-on work computer work with econometric software packages (Eviews).","info_instructors":["CHOW HWEE KWAN"]}},"ECON723":{"name":"Urban Economics","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - PhD Econs","info_units":0.5,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Economics","info_academic_organization":"School of Eco