(ii) discover knowledge from social media and social networks; and (iii) apply the knowledge they have discovered on business problems.\n\nThis course first introduces Python programming, as Python is the preliminary programming language used in this course. With enough skills on the programming language, students are taught on building crawlers to get data from social networks. Such data include both social media data and social network data. However, social network data may not be as explicit as social media data due to the fact that different social networks structure their data about their customers and relationships among customers including customers’ behaviors in different ways. Students need to understand such differences, and extract social networks from various aspects that they deem important and relevant to some business applications in mind.\n\nThere are two categories of data mining techniques to be introduced for social media data and social network data respectively, namely, text mining techniques to analyze topics and sentiments of social media, and graph mining techniques to analyze structures of social networks. The main focus of this course is on graph mining techniques over text mining techniques since there is already an elective for text mining – text analytics and application (B.7). Since graph theory is not taught for undergraduate programs in most universities, this course will spend some time to get students familiarized with graph theory before introducing graph mining techniques.\n\nPlenty of social analytics methods originate from graph mining techniques, students should first understand these techniques in order to apply these methods appropriately on social networks. In general, students will develop the ability to abstract social networks into graph models, and to extend graph algorithms to applications on social networks. Besides graph mining techniques, this course will also discuss social influence and social links which are more unique to social networks than graphs. There are also three advanced topics including ego networks and community detection catered for modern social networks analytics.\n\nLast but not least, students are expected to apply a mixture between text mining algorithms and graph mining algorithms on social media and social network data, with some business applications they have already in mind when extracting social networks, as their course projects to demonstrate a set of full-stack abilities from developments to analytics, knowledge discovery, and even further to business applications.","info_instructors":["FANG YUAN"]}},"IDST713":{"name":"Independent Study","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - PhD Business (OM)","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_academic_organization":"LKCSB GPO","info_description":"Each independent study is a one-on-one research tutorial between the student and a selected faculty, on a topic mutually agreed upon by the student and the faculty. A research term paper is required in each independent study.","info_instructors":["GAO YINI","LIM YUN FONG","ZHENG ZHICHAO"," DANIEL"]}},"ISFS613":{"name":"Analytics in Financial Services","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - IT in Business","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Information Systems","info_academic_organization":"School of Info Systems MITB","info_description":"Every bank is collecting ever-increasing large amounts of data every day. With such massive amounts of data collected and huge potential value that are found in these data for marketing, risk management or other purposes, the demand for analytics professional to make sense of these data is increasing. \n\nThe skills and knowledge that are needed for analytics professional in the banks would require a wide array of skills such as data management, analysis, mathematics & statistics, business and not forgetting intimate knowledge of the financial services domain, especially regulations and compliance. \n\nThe module aims to bring these skills and knowledge together, to bridge the gap between analytics techniques and their applications in financial institutions. Using current applications of analytics in financial institution, coupled with class discussion, labs and guest speakers from the industry, the students can understand how domain knowledge (such as banking objectives and regulations) interacts with the other areas of the analytics value chain. \n\nThis module is also designed to take advantage of the diversity in students’ background to give varied points-of-view during each lab projects and discussion. This closely emulates many bank’s analytics environment. To ensure students have the required level of knowledge and skills, pre-requisites are set.\n\nAfter the module, students would be able to identify potential areas with consideration on the current banking landscape shaped by regional and local regulators, being able to state down the challenges in the implementation, allowing them to propose valuable analytics solutions that are actionable by the financial institutions. This will give them an edge in their financial services analytics career.","info_instructors":["MA NANG LAIK"]}},"IS613":{"name":"Cybersecurity Technology and Applications","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - IT in Business","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Information Systems","info_academic_organization":"School of Info Systems MITB","info_description":"This course provides an introduction to cybersecurity. The focus is on fundamental concepts, system design principles, basic cryptographic techniques, protocols, access control models, firewalls and intrusion