, operational risk and personnel risk. This component of the course will include detailed discussion of the due diligence guidelines of the Alternative Investment Mangers’ Association, hence the focus is on a practical understanding of the day-to-day risks and key issues faced by hedge fund managers. Investor monitoring and selection of hedge funds for investment purposes will also be discussed.\n\nSecondly, the course also provides an introduction to systematic investing strategies that may be employed by hedge funds. An overview of strategy types is provided, after which the students will be provided with (and are expected to be able to discuss) a range of practical examples of systematic strategy tools and techniques, including strategy implementation.\n\nCase study discussions are employed to provide practical examples of key issues introduced in this course.\n\nIt is intended that one or more guest speakers from the industry will present their personal experiences to provide students with a perspective on opportunities and advancement within hedge funds and related financial institutions.\n\nThis course places substantial emphasis on active student participation. Classes should be viewed as discussion seminars, NOT instructor lectures. It is expected that students will have read assigned material prior to the class, and ALL students are expected to be able to discuss key issues with the instructor during classes.","info_instructors":["HAMISH MACALISTER"]}},"FNCE648A":{"name":"Alternative Investments","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - Financial Economics","info_units":0.5,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"School of Economics","info_academic_organization":"SOE MFE","info_description":"This course provides both a theoretical and practical look into the world of managing Alternative investments and their role in a multi-asset class portfolio.","info_instructors":["SAYANTA"]}}