pants with a basis for working with and advising business leaders in developing strategic social value alignment, and engage customers through social marketing, and build and understanding of firm level social strategy, dynamics of relationships between companies and stakeholders. Leaders of non-profit and government agencies will also find the module of benefit as it covers public-private relationships and will help identify how to work with business leaders on areas of business responsibility. \n\nSocial issues are wide a varied and include environmental management, health, education, social justice, labour standards, social mobility, climate change, and more. A full treatment of these topics is beyond the scope of this module. Instead, this module will provide broad frameworks and analytical tools for managing social value and stakeholder relationships, and provide illustrative examples though a guest speaker series to bring ideas to life. “Learning by doing” is the centre piece of this course which features a practicum style project where a team will work on realizing greater value for a firm they select to support.","info_instructors":["Staff"]}},"MGMT222":{"name":"Family Business","data":{"info_career":"Undergraduate","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_academic_organization":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_description":"Family businesses are the most prevalent form of business in the world. It is also an emerging and vibrant area of interest today among academics, practitioners and students of management. This course explores the unique challenges and opportunities involves in ownership and management of family businesses. Key family, ownership and management issues relevant to the management and continuity of these enterprises will be covered. Topics in this course include the uniqueness of family business, su