nsist of complex interactions between human activity and the environment. The course will apply several academic perspectives to characterizing these problems and their possible solutions. The course first examines how particular patterns of economic and social development are manifested in past practices and developmental paths, such as unsustainable patterns of urbanization and industrialization. The private sector is an integral part of many problems and solutions, and as such, will be the main focus of the course. An important part of addressing sustainability is the use of various frameworks to help incorporate a sustainability perspective into firms’ strategies and operations. These often employ a systems perspective. To help characterize firm’ sustainability and determine appropriate courses of action, the course will cover also specific managerial tools and frameworks that help to characterize sustainability challenges and incorporate them into corporate plans include the Triple Bottom Line, Life-Cycle Assessment, and the Base of the Pyramid approach and its business models. Where necessary, material on and links to concepts of strategy, business models, stakeholder engagement, public policy (in terms of governance), and innovation will be made.While many of the sustainability concepts have a Western origin, because of our location in Asia, and the increasing importance of sustainability to the local and regional context, especial attention has been paid to relating each section of the course to Asia, even as the original material (concepts and experiences) is covered from the (non-Asian) country or region of origin. This will be done through a series of cases and examples, especially for the part of the course covering industrialization- and poverty-related sustainability issues. Examples of Asia-specific material introduced in past classes and continued this year include material on the early phases of Japan’s industrialization and pollution and its eventual social-regulatory reforms; China’s ongoing sustainability problems as it continues to industrialize; China’s renewable energy policy and planning; agro-based eco-industrial parks (industrial ecosystems) in Turkey; the ongoing poverty issues in the region, and solutions (technological and otherwise) as practiced in India and Bangladesh); and finally, issues that Singapore faces. Similarly, the poor in the East and in other developing regions face many of the same issues as seen in other developing and developed regions, and so cross-comparisons between different regions can yield many lessons.","info_instructors":["TED FEICHIN TSCHANG","Staff"]}},"MGMT706":{"name":"International Business Theories","data":{"info_career":"Graduate - PhD Business (SMO)","info_units":1.0,"info_grading_basis":"Graded","info_course_components":"Seminar Required","info_campus":"Main Campus","info_academic_group":"Lee Kong Chian Sch of Business","info_academic_organization":"LKCSB GPO","info_description":"The goal of this course is to provide a solid theoretical basis for further research in International Business and Management. The course will survey efficiency-based theories and empirical studies of the existence and scope of the multinational enterprise (MNE) and its alternatives, such as long-term contracts, licensing and franchising. We will also discuss (1) the strategies used by firms to enter foreign markets, such as ownership and establishment mode strategies, (2) the costs facing firms entering foreign markets, and (3) the dynamics of their foreign expansion. Hence the main question that this course will discuss is “why do MNEs exist, and what determines the strategies they follow.”\n\nGiven the limited time available, we will not directly discuss theories of international trade and comparative advantage, international finance, interactions of multinational firms and governments, and the impact of multinational firms on competition. However, what we will discuss has important b